metadata.name: MOYO #75
metadata.description:
MOYO is generative piece building unique patterns.
The first algorithm was created in 2018, while visiting Kanazawa, a city on the west side of Japan.
Originally inspired by some kimono embroidery, I created some set of rules that will give life, recursively, to patterns generated inside a squared area.

Thanks to fxhash, I can pursue the original generative vision of those patterns by evolving the algorithm, and here comes MOYO.
This collection of 1024 pieces waiting to be minted offers new compositions, new rules and new colors.
During the iterative crafting process, I've been surprised by the algorithm which offered some unexpected kind of results, which have been kept for the final generation.

Artist: Florian Zumbrunn
@florianzumbrunn

metadata.name: Bindu #55
metadata.description:
The series employs fractal circles to create repeating patterns, using a monochrome color palette on the canvas. The number, size, and density of circles as well as the level of recursion, vary across pieces. The introduction of these variations and arcs adds a new dimension to fractals by juxtaposing their self-similar nature at all scales with elements of randomness.

This is my third series in a row that features a monochromatic color palette. There's something about the limitation of using only binary colors that enables me to appreciate abstraction purely for its form.

Note on the name: The series draws its name from Sayed Haider Raza of the Bombay Progressive Artists' Group. I have always admired Raza‚Äôs use of sacred geometry and his abstract work has forever been a source of inspiration. Raza believed that ‚ÄòBindu‚Äô (the dot, point or circle) is the ultimate point of creation, representing the universe in its entirety.

Implemented in JS, this code utilizes the Perlin.js and Simple-noise.js libraries.

Press p to save a png of the image in full screen. Press s to save an svg file.

Pixel Love!

metadata.name: SOUND GROWS INTO SPACE #64
metadata.description:
This poem was created for THE PASSAGE: Pitch Drop, an interactive minting experience where your choices determine the design of your token. 

To take part, please purchase an Edition 5 Coin on fx(hash) by HERE & NOW. The artwork and experience draw inspiration from the ‚ÄúThe Pitch Drop Experiment,‚Äù the world's longest-running laboratory experiment. Since 1927, only nine drops of pitch have fallen, never witnessed live.

____


SOUND GROWS INTO SPACE is a token word performance of an ars autopoetica written by Sasha Stiles and her AI-powered alter ego, Technelegy, with original music by Kris Bones. It is part of Stiles‚Äô ongoing REPETAE series, which explores the resonances between poetic repetition and algorithmic recursion ‚Äî how, in poetry as in generative art, meaning accrues through reiteration, and emotion is unlocked through the development and interruption of pattern. A conceptually and literally interactive text, SOUND GROWS INTO SPACE uses the self-replicating page provided by fx(hash) to invite close contemplation of how language is shaped and received via intimate, visceral aesthetics such as voice, visuals and melody/beat, and regenerated with every encounter.

Poetry endures across space and the passage of time precisely because of a paradox: it is immutable yet intensely personal, becoming something irrefutably unique with each and every reader. In this poem, shifting parameters influence the flow of feeling and understanding, imbuing verse with multidimensional meaning and empowering deep engagement in the act of reading.

____


SOUND GROWS INTO SPACE

By Sasha Stiles & Technelegy

Sound grows 
into space
like a breath 
taken by storm.

Heartbeat
in the brain
was my first taste 
of the word.

Language flips 
in my chest
like a fly
in a jar.

The song 
learns to climb
all the air
in the world.

Time is music
to my ears
filling the emptiness 
with its own rhythms.

There is no such thing 
as silence,
only the echo 
of time‚Äôs longing.

____


For more info: https://hereandnow.events/
To participate in the event: https://www.fxhash.xyz/generative/slug/here-and-now:-edition-5

metadata.name: Polar Grid #1041
metadata.description:
Polar Grid is part of the fxhash live minting experience at Proof of People, London 2022.

This is a study of color, motion, and composition, and an homage to cinema as an artform. Colorful shapes overlap and pulse in a ever repeating dance. An abstracted movie experience. Each color palette in the series (except one) is inspired by a different film director (if you want a real challenge, see how many you can guess without looking at the feature names).

The palettes were extracted from movie stills or movie posters and fine tuned by hand. As often, I have to thank independent tool makers for their indirect help. My gratitude goes to David Aerne for FarbV√©lo and Fabrizio Bianchi for Coolors.

The code for Polar Grid is based on early iterations of what ultimately became my carat series. Both projects come from the same fascination for color as a system, even though I used a different approach here. You could call this a carat prequel.

The animation is done using a technique called polar noise. This makes it so the motion of all elements ends up repeating in the same amount of time. This is useful for generating motion that loops perfectly while still appearing organic. In this particular case, the animation repeats every œÄ √ó 100 seconds.

A challenge in building any generative system is to find the right balance between coherence and variety. I designed the system with the large edition size in mind. During development I generated hundreds of iterations and tweaked my code to make sure that every iteration is truly unique and fits the overall aesthetic of the collection.

I truly hope you will enjoy your own little abstract movie.

‚Äî Rapha√´l de Courville


Released: July 6th 2022

Medium: p5.js, html canvas, css

Reference: sk220621


**About the artist**

Rapha√´l de Courville is a generative artist, streamer, and educator. His artistic work is an exploration of generative systems, patterns, interactivity, and time. Born in Paris, he lives and works in Berlin.

metadata.name: Complicare #29
metadata.description:
Complicare is my first "still" generative work, and an exercise in minimalism.

Inspired by pioneers like Sol Lewitt and Frank Stella, as well as current fx_hash artists such as Rev Dan Catt and Yazid, this work attempts to balance a diverse visual output with a restricted generative system. I also wanted to focus on honing my abilities to add texture to the digital canvas, taking cues from other great artists on here like William Mapan and Hevey.

Each piece has one of 17 different layouts and one of 6 different color palettes.

Thanks to all of the artists on fx_hash for inspiring me every day to make more art, and particularly to dcarcher for some really insightful artistic perspective and feedback.
